Reason: To predict the melting point of 4-nitrobenzaldehyde semicarbazone, we will take into account the functional groups present in the molecule and how they affect the melting point in comparison to benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The nitro group (-NO2) increases the melting point due to its strong electron-withdrawing nature and ability to form intramolecular hydrogen bonds, and we estimate that to be +80°C. The aldehyde group (CHO) can participate in hydrogen bonding and increases rigidity, especially when part of a semicarbazone, so we estimate an increase of +70°C. The semicarbazone moiety itself is a combination of a carbonyl and a hydrazine functional group, which allows for extensive hydrogen bonding and increases melting point significantly; we estimate an enhancement of another +120°C. Summing these predicted contributions, we would estimate an overall increase of 270°C to the base value of benzene.
Prediction: 5.5 (base value for benzene) + 80 (nitro group) + 70 (aldehyde in semicarbazone) + 120 (semicarbazone) = 275.5°C
